18 (c) If a public agency does not respond to a request for a record
19 under this section:
20 (1) within twenty-four (24) hours of receiving the request for a
21 record from a person who:
22 (A) is physically present in the agency office;
23 (B) makes the request by telephone; or
24 (C) requests enhanced access to a document; or
25 (2) within seven (7) days of receiving the request for a record
26 made by mail, or by facsimile, or through an electronic portal
27 under section 3.3 of this chapter;
28 the request for the record is deemed denied. The person requesting the
29 information may appeal the denial under section 9 of this chapter.
30 (d) If a public agency refuses to confirm or deny the existence of a
31 record under this section, the name and title or position of the person
32 responsible for the refusal shall be given to the person making the
33 records request.
34 (e) A person who has received a refusal from an agency to confirm
35 or deny the existence of a record may file an action in the circuit or
36 superior court of the county in which the response was received:
37 (1) to compel the public agency to confirm whether the record
38 exists or does not exist; and
39 (2) if the public agency confirms that the record exists, to compel
40 the agency to permit the person to inspect and copy the record.
41 (f) The court shall determine the matter de novo, with the burden of
42 proof on the public agency to sustain its refusal to confirm or deny the
HB 1360—LS 6876/DI 119

8
1 existence of the record. The public agency meets its burden of proof by
2 filing a public affidavit with the court that provides with reasonable
3 specificity of detail, and not simply conclusory statements, the basis of
4 the agency's claim that it cannot be required to confirm or deny the
5 existence of the requested record. If the public agency meets its burden
6 of proof, the burden of proof shifts to the person requesting access to
7 the record. The person requesting access to the record meets the
8 person's burden of proof by proving any of the following:
9 (1) The agency's justifications for not confirming the existence of
10 the record contradict other evidence in the trial record.
11 (2) The agency is withholding the record in bad faith.
12 (3) An official with authority to speak for the agency has
13 acknowledged to the public in a documented disclosure that the
14 record exists. The person requesting the record must prove that
15 the information requested:
16 (A) is as specific as the information previously disclosed; and
17 (B) matches the previously disclosed information.
18 (g) Either party may make an interlocutory appeal of the trial court's
19 determination on whether the agency's refusal to confirm or deny the
20 existence of the record was proper.
21 (h) If the court, after the disposition of any interlocutory appeals,
22 finds that the agency's refusal to confirm or deny was improper, the
23 court shall order the agency to disclose whether the record exists or
24 does not exist. If the record exists and the agency claims that the record
25 is exempt from disclosure under this chapter, the court may review the
26 public record in camera to determine whether any part of the record
27 may be withheld.
28 (i) In an action filed under this section, the court shall award
29 reasonable attorney's fees, court costs, and other reasonable expenses
30 of litigation to the prevailing party if:
31 (1) the plaintiff substantially prevails; or
32 (2) the defendant substantially prevails and the court finds the
33 action was frivolous or vexatious.
34 A plaintiff is eligible for the awarding of attorney's fees, court costs,
35 and other reasonable expenses regardless of whether the plaintiff filed
36 the action without first seeking and receiving an informal inquiry
37 response or advisory opinion from the public access counselor.
38 (j) A court that hears an action under this section may not assess a
39 civil penalty under section 9.5 of this chapter in connection with the
40 action.
