33 1, 2026]: Sec. 8.1. (a) A public agency may give priority in fulfilling
34 public records requests to:
35 (1) Indiana residents; and
36 (2) requests submitted for civic, journalistic, academic, or
37 personal use.
38 (b) Requests identified as originating from out-of-state entities
39 or automated systems may be:
40 (1) delayed as necessary to prevent disruption of core agency
41 functions; and
42 (2) subject to a fee under section 8(n) of this chapter.
HB 1360—LS 6876/DI 119

13
1 SECTION 6. IC 5-14-3-9, AS AMENDED BY P.L.58-2016,
2 SECTION 8, IS AMENDED TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
3 JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 9. (a) This section does not apply to a request for
4 information under section 4.4 of this chapter.
5 (b) A denial of disclosure by a public agency occurs when the
6 person making the request is physically present in the office of the
7 agency, makes the request by telephone, or requests enhanced access
8 to a document and:
9 (1) the person designated by the public agency as being
10 responsible for public records release decisions refuses to permit
11 inspection and copying of a public record when a request has
12 been made; or
13 (2) twenty-four (24) hours elapse after any employee of the public
14 agency refuses to permit inspection and copying of a public
15 record when a request has been made;
16 whichever occurs first.
17 (c) If a person requests by mail or by facsimile a copy or copies of
18 a public record by mail, by facsimile, or through an electronic
19 portal under section 3.3 of this chapter, a denial of disclosure does
20 not occur until seven (7) days have elapsed from the date the public
21 agency receives the request.
22 (d) If a request is made orally, either in person or by telephone, a
23 public agency may deny the request orally. However, if a request
24 initially is made in writing, by facsimile, or through enhanced access,
25 or if an oral request that has been denied is renewed in writing or by
26 facsimile, a public agency may deny the request if:
27 (1) the denial is in writing or by facsimile; and
28 (2) the denial includes:
29 (A) a statement of the specific exemption or exemptions
30 authorizing the withholding of all or part of the public record;
31 and
32 (B) the name and the title or position of the person responsible
33 for the denial.
34 (e) A person who has been denied the right to inspect or copy a
35 public record by a public agency may file an action in the circuit or
36 superior court of the county in which the denial occurred to compel the
37 public agency to permit the person to inspect and copy the public
38 record. Whenever an action is filed under this subsection, the public
39 agency must notify each person who supplied any part of the public
40 record at issue:
41 (1) that a request for release of the public record has been denied;
42 and
HB 1360—LS 6876/DI 119

14
1 (2) whether the denial was in compliance with an informal inquiry
2 response or advisory opinion of the public access counselor.
3 Such persons are entitled to intervene in any litigation that results from
4 the denial. The person who has been denied the right to inspect or copy
5 need not allege or prove any special damage different from that
6 suffered by the public at large.
7 (f) The court shall determine the matter de novo, with the burden of
8 proof on the public agency to sustain its denial. If the issue in de novo
9 review under this section is whether a public agency properly denied
10 access to a public record because the record is exempted under section
11 4(a) of this chapter, the public agency meets its burden of proof under
12 this subsection by establishing the content of the record with adequate
13 specificity and not by relying on a conclusory statement or affidavit.
14 (g) This subsection does not apply to an action under section 5.2 of
15 this chapter. If the issue in a de novo review under this section is
16 whether a public agency properly denied access to a public record
17 because the record is exempted under section 4(b) of this chapter:
18 (1) the public agency meets its burden of proof under this
19 subsection by:
20 (A) proving that:
21 (i) the record falls within any one (1) of the categories of
22 exempted records under section 4(b) of this chapter; and
23 (ii) if the action is for denial of access to a recording under
24 section 5.1 of this chapter, the plaintiff is not a "requestor"
25 as that term is defined in section 5.1 of this chapter; and
26 (B) establishing the content of the record with adequate
27 specificity and not by relying on a conclusory statement or
28 affidavit; and
29 (2) a person requesting access to a public record meets the
30 person's burden of proof under this subsection by proving that the
31 denial of access is arbitrary or capricious.
32 (h) The court may review the public record in camera to determine
33 whether any part of it may be withheld under this chapter. However, if
34 the complaint alleges that a public agency denied disclosure of a public
35 record by redacting information in the public record, the court shall
36 conduct an in camera inspection of the public record with the redacted
37 information included.
38 (i) Except as provided in subsection (k), in any action filed under
39 this section, a court shall award reasonable attorney's fees, court costs,
40 and other reasonable expenses of litigation to the prevailing party if:
41 (1) the plaintiff substantially prevails; or
42 (2) the defendant substantially prevails and the court finds the
HB 1360—LS 6876/DI 119

15
1 action was frivolous or vexatious.
2 Except as provided in subsection (k), the plaintiff is not eligible for the
3 awarding of attorney's fees, court costs, and other reasonable expenses
4 if the plaintiff filed the action without first seeking and receiving an
5 informal inquiry response or advisory opinion from the public access
6 counselor, unless the plaintiff can show the filing of the action was
7 necessary because the denial of access to a public record under this
8 chapter would prevent the plaintiff from presenting that public record
9 to a public agency preparing to act on a matter of relevance to the
10 public record whose disclosure was denied.
11 (j) Except as provided in subsection (k), a court may assess a civil
12 penalty under section 9.5 of this chapter only if the plaintiff obtained
13 an advisory opinion from the public access counselor before filing an
14 action under this section as set forth in section 9.5 of this chapter.
15 (k) This subsection applies only to an action to appeal the denial of
16 access to a law enforcement recording under section 5.1 of this chapter.
17 A requestor (as defined in section 5.1 of this chapter) may bring an
18 action to appeal from the denial of access to a law enforcement
19 recording without first seeking or receiving an informal inquiry
20 response or advisory opinion from the public access counselor. If the
21 requestor prevails in an action under this subsection:
22 (1) the requestor is eligible for an award of reasonable attorney's
23 fees, court costs, and other reasonable expenses; and
24 (2) a court may assess a civil penalty under section 9.5 of this
25 chapter.
26 (l) A court shall expedite the hearing of an action filed under this
27 section.
28 SECTION 7. IC 5-14-3-11 IS ADDED TO THE INDIANA CODE
29 AS A NEW SECTION TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE JULY
30 1, 2026]: Sec. 11. In addition to providing the public access
31 counselor with notice of a request to which the public agency has
32 declined to respond under section 3.3 of this chapter, a public
33 agency shall report to the public access counselor, through a
34 standardized mechanism prescribed by the public access counselor,
35 any public records request received by the public agency that is
36 suspected by the public agency of being:
37 (1) automated; or
38 (2) data scraping or phishing activity.
