11 SECTION 11. IC 5-14-4-10 IS AMENDED TO READ AS
12 FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE JULY 1, 2026]: Sec. 10. The counselor has
13 the following powers and duties:
14 (1) To establish and administer a program to train public officials
15 and educate the public on the rights of the public and the
16 responsibilities of public agencies under the public access laws.
17 The counselor may contract with a person or a public or private
18 entity to fulfill the counselor's responsibility under this
19 subdivision.
20 (2) To conduct research.
21 (3) To prepare interpretive and educational materials and
22 programs in cooperation with the office of the attorney general.
23 (4) To distribute to newly elected or appointed public officials the
24 public access laws and educational materials concerning the
25 public access laws.
26 (5) To respond to informal inquiries made by the public and
27 public agencies by telephone, in writing, in person, by facsimile,
28 or by electronic mail concerning the public access laws.
29 (6) To issue advisory opinions to interpret the public access laws
30 upon the request of a person or a public agency. However, the
31 counselor may not issue an advisory opinion concerning a specific
32 matter with respect to which a lawsuit has been filed under
33 IC 5-14-1.5 or IC 5-14-3.
34 (7) To make recommendations to the general assembly
35 concerning ways to improve public access.
36 (8) To coordinate with public agencies to:
37 (A) track the volume and nature of public records requests
38 received by public agencies; and
39 (B) identify patterns or sources of excessive, automated,
40 phishing related, or data scraping based public records
41 requests.
42 (9) To establish a standardized mechanism by which public
